div></div></div></div></div><p id=3D"b615" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph =
nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok o=
l hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">In this post I am going to share wi=
th you a different perspective about getting started with writing code for =
Android. The standard approach is installing Android Studio and building a =
simple =E2=80=9CHello World=E2=80=9D app in Java or Kotlin. But it can also=
 be done differently, as you will shortly see. But first, a little backgrou=
nd story =E2=80=94</p><h3 id=3D"ed7c" class=3D"om on ho bb oo op oq ec or o=
s ot ee ou nz ov ow ox od oy oz pa oh pb pc pd pe bg" data-selectable-parag=
raph=3D"">How Does my Android Phone Work?</h3><p id=3D"7498" class=3D"pw-po=
st-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im pf nu nv ip pg nx ny nz ph ob oc od pi o=
f og oh pj oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">One evening my li=
fe partner <span class=3D"pm"><span class=3D"bi" aria-describedby=3D"14" ar=
ia-labelledby=3D"14" role=3D"tooltip"><div tabindex=3D"-1" class=3D"ba"><a =
class=3D"pk pl fi" href=3D"https://medium.com/u/4167b3cd8d4b?source=3Dpost_=
page---user_mention--30e8e0f8c3fe---------------------------------------" r=
el=3D"noopener" target=3D"_blank">Ariella Eliassaf</a></div></span></span> =
asked me: How does my smartphone work? What=E2=80=99s inside it? How does i=
t electricity, ones and zeroes, make it all work?</p><p id=3D"5fd8" class=
=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob o=
c od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">Ariella =
wasn=E2=80=99t foreign to programming. In fact, she even did <a class=3D"z =
pn" href=3D"https://twitter.com/urishaked/status/719288164318371840" rel=3D=
"noopener ugc nofollow" target=3D"_blank">some Arduino projects</a> which i=
nvolved both programming and electronics. Perhaps that=E2=80=99s what made =
her hungry to know more. Luckily, one of the Computer Science courses in th=
e university addressed exactly this =E2=80=94 or, at least, gave me enough =
background to research a good answer.</p><p id=3D"6fd4" class=3D"pw-post-bo=
dy-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og =
oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">We spent the next coup=
le of weeks going from the very basics =E2=80=94 how microscopic impurities=
 in silicon lattice alter their properties, turning them into semi-conducto=
rs, and the way electron flow through this semi conductors can be controlle=
d, forming a transistors. We then went one level higher, I showed her how l=
ogic gates such as <a class=3D"z pn" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
NAND_gate" rel=3D"noopener ugc nofollow" target=3D"_blank">NAND</a> and NOR=
 can be built by combining transistors in a specific way.</p><p id=3D"7954"=
 class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz o=
a ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">We=
 continued exploring different kind of logic gates, and combining them to d=
o calculations (such as adding two binary numbers) and memory cells (flip-f=
lops). Once we had that nailed, we designed a simple, imaginary CPU that co=
ntained two general purpose registers, and a couple of simple instructions =
(like adding two registers), and wrote a simple program that would multiply=
 these two numbers.</p><p id=3D"ddcb" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr=
 ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh =
bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">If you wish to get familiar with the abo=
ve, check out <a class=3D"z pn" href=3D"https://eater.net/8bit" rel=3D"noop=
ener ugc nofollow" target=3D"_blank">the 8-bit computer from scratch tutori=
al</a> =E2=80=94 it explains pretty much everything from the basics. I wish=
 I knew about it back then!</p><h3 id=3D"0706" class=3D"om on ho bb oo op o=
q ec or os ot ee ou nz ov ow ox od oy oz pa oh pb pc pd pe bg" data-selecta=
ble-paragraph=3D"">Hello, Android!</h3><p id=3D"26f7" class=3D"pw-post-body=
-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im pf nu nv ip pg nx ny nz ph ob oc od pi of og oh=
 pj oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">At this point, I felt sh=
e had enough background to explore how the CPU of her smartphone worked. Sh=
e had a Galaxy S6 Edge device, which is based on the ARM architecture (like=
 the majority of the smartphones do). It was time to write =E2=80=9CHello, =
World=E2=80=9D, her first Android app ever, but in assembly:</p><figure cla=
ss=3D"po pp pq pr ps pt"><div class=3D"pu ge e fv"><div class=3D"pv pw e"><=
iframe src=3D"cid:frame-9BDC3BF6DEB7F1D37EDC05131CE9F0AC@mhtml.blink" allow=
fullscreen=3D"" frameborder=3D"0" height=3D"0" width=3D"0" title=3D"android=
-hello-world.s" class=3D"ga g hc ea bd" scrolling=3D"no"></iframe></div></d=
iv></figure><p id=3D"37cc" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im=
 nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-se=
lectable-paragraph=3D"">If you have never seen assembly code before, this p=
rogram can be quite intimidating, but don=E2=80=99t worry =E2=80=94 we=E2=
=80=99ll go over it together.</p><p id=3D"19c4" class=3D"pw-post-body-parag=
raph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj=
 ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">The program is divided into tw=
o sections: <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">text</code> , which contains t=
he machine code instructions, and <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">data</co=
de>, starting in line 15, which contains variables, strings and other data.=
 The <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">.text</code> section is usually read-=
only, whereas the <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">.data</code> section can=
 also be written to.</p><p id=3D"7d1e" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq n=
r ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh=
 bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">In line 2, we define a global function =
called <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">_start</code>. This is the entry po=
int of the program. In other words, the operating system will start running=
 you code from this point. The actual definition of the function is in line=
 number 4.</p><p id=3D"4836" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b =
im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-=
selectable-paragraph=3D"">The function does two things: line 5=E2=80=939 pr=
int the message to the screen, and lines 11=E2=80=9313 terminate the progra=
m. You could actually remove lines 11=E2=80=9313 and the program will strin=
g print =E2=80=9CHello, World=E2=80=9D and exit, but it wouldn=E2=80=99t be=
 a clean exit =E2=80=94 it will just crash trying to execute some random in=
valid instruction which happens to be next in memory.</p><p id=3D"01a3" cla=
ss=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob=
 oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">Printi=
ng to the screen is done by calling a system call. A system call is a funct=
ion provided by the operating system. We call the <a class=3D"z pn" href=3D=
"http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man2/write.2.html" rel=3D"noopener ugc nof=
ollow" target=3D"_blank">write()</a> system call, which we indicate by load=
ing the value 4 into a CPU register called <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b"=
>r7</code> (line 8), and then execute the <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">=
swi $0</code> instruction (line 9), which <a class=3D"z pn" href=3D"http://=
infocenter.arm.com/help/index.jsp?topic=3D%2Fcom.arm.doc.dui0204f%2FCihidab=
i.html" rel=3D"noopener ugc nofollow" target=3D"_blank">jumps</a> right int=
o the Linux kernel running inside Android.</p><p id=3D"4e8e" class=3D"pw-po=
st-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe o=
f og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">The parameters fo=
r the system call are passed through the other registers: <code class=3D"db=
 px py pz qa b">r0</code> indicates the number of the file descriptor we wa=
nt to print to. We put there the value 1 (line 5), which indicated stdout, =
the standard output, or in other words =E2=80=94 printing to the screen.</p=
><p id=3D"92b1" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv i=
p nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-pa=
ragraph=3D""><code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">r1</code> indicates the memor=
y address of the data we want to write, so we load there the address of the=
 =E2=80=9CHello, World=E2=80=9D string (line 6), and <code class=3D"db px p=
y pz qa b">r2</code> tells Android how many bytes we want to write. We set =
it to the value of <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">message_len</code> (lin=
e 7), which is calculated in line 18 using a special syntax: the dot symbol=
 denotes the current memory address, so <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">. =
- message</code> means the current memory address minus the address of <cod=
e class=3D"db px py pz qa b">message</code>. Since we define <code class=3D=
"db px py pz qa b">message_len</code> immediately after <code class=3D"db p=
x py pz qa b">message</code>, this evaluates to the length of <code class=
=3D"db px py pz qa b">message</code>.</p><p id=3D"2ce5" class=3D"pw-post-bo=
dy-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og =
oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">So to sum up, the code=
 in lines 5=E2=80=939 is the equivalent of the following c code:</p><pre cl=
ass=3D"po pp pq pr ps qb qa qc qd ae qe bg"><span id=3D"ff4c" class=3D"om o=
n ho qa b qf qg qh e qi qj" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">#define message =
"Hello, World\n"<br>write(1, message, sizeof(message));</span></pre><p id=
=3D"238f" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw n=
x ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragrap=
h=3D"">Terminating the program is much simpler =E2=80=94 we simply need to =
load the exit code into <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">r0</code> (line 11=
), and then we load the value 1, which is the number of the <a class=3D"z p=
n" href=3D"https://linux.die.net/man/2/exit" rel=3D"noopener ugc nofollow" =
target=3D"_blank">exit()</a> system call, into <code class=3D"db px py pz q=
a b">r7</code> (line 12), and call the kernel again (line 13).</p><div clas=
s=3D"wh wi wj wk v j cs"><div class=3D"wl wm wn wo wp e fj"><h2 class=3D"wq=
 b wr ws wt wu wv">Get Uri Shaked=E2=80=99s stories in&nbsp;your&nbsp;inbox=
</h2></div><div class=3D"cp e fj"><p class=3D"bb b bc u dy">Join Medium for=
 free to get updates from&nbsp;this&nbsp;writer.</p></div><div class=3D"wz =
sj xa xb si xc v"><span class=3D"bb b bc u bg"><div class=3D"xd v cs"><div =
class=3D"v xd fg ff bl xe xf db mf xg xh xi xj xk xl xm"><input class=3D"xn=
 af ac ah xo xp gg lq bh xq bd" placeholder=3D"Enter your email" type=3D"te=
