h bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">After getting the NDK, you will need t=
o search for a file called <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">arm-linux-andro=
ideabi-as</code>, the assembler for the ARM platform. If you downloaded it =
through Android Studio, look for it inside the Android SDK Location. On my =
machine I found the file in the following location inside the SDK:</p><pre =
class=3D"po pp pq pr ps qb qa qc qd ae qe bg"><span id=3D"a0dd" class=3D"om=
 on ho qa b qf qg qh e qi qj" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">ndk-bundle\too=
lchains\arm-linux-androideabi-4.9\prebuilt\windows-x86_64\bin</span></pre><=
p id=3D"f184" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip =
nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-para=
graph=3D"">As you can imagine, it will slightly change based on your exact =
NDK version and operating system. The important thing is that it has the AR=
M assembler inside.</p><p id=3D"6ddf" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr=
 ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh =
bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">One you located the assembler, save your=
 source code into a file called <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">hello.s</c=
ode> (<code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">s</code> is a commonly used extensio=
n for assembly files in GNU systems). Then run the following command to con=
vert it into machine code:</p><pre class=3D"po pp pq pr ps qb qa qc qd ae q=
e bg"><span id=3D"e7ff" class=3D"om on ho qa b qf qg qh e qi qj" data-selec=
table-paragraph=3D"">arm-linux-androideabi-as -o hello.o hello.s</span></pr=
e><p id=3D"850f" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv =
ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-p=
aragraph=3D"">This will create an object file called <code class=3D"db px p=
y pz qa b">hello.o</code>. Only one more step is needed to convert this int=
o an ELF binary that can run on your device =E2=80=94 calling the linker:</=
p><pre class=3D"po pp pq pr ps qb qa qc qd ae qe bg"><span id=3D"9caf" clas=
s=3D"om on ho qa b qf qg qh e qi qj" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">arm-lin=
ux-androideabi-ld -o hello hello.o</span></pre><p id=3D"c42a" class=3D"pw-p=
ost-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe =
of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">That=E2=80=99s i=
t! You now have a file called <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">hello</code>=
 that contains your program, ready to run.</p><h3 id=3D"fd06" class=3D"om o=
n ho bb oo op oq ec or os ot ee ou nz ov ow ox od oy oz pa oh pb pc pd pe b=
g" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">Running The Program on Your Device</h3><p=
 id=3D"46f3" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im pf nu nv ip p=
g nx ny nz ph ob oc od pi of og oh pj oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-parag=
raph=3D"">Android programs are usually distributed in APK format. This is a=
 special kind of ZIP file, which Android expect to be constructed in a spec=
ific way, and should include Java classes (you can write parts of your app =
using native C/C++ code, but the entry point still needs to be Java).</p><p=
 id=3D"39f8" class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip n=
w nx ny nz oa ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-parag=
raph=3D"">I wanted to avoid this complexity when running our app, so we use=
d <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">adb</code> to copy it over to the temp f=
older of her Android device, and then <code class=3D"db px py pz qa b">adb =
shell</code> to run the app and see the output:</p><pre class=3D"po pp pq p=
r ps qb qa qc qd ae qe bg"><span id=3D"c8c8" class=3D"om on ho qa b qf qg q=
h e qi qj" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">adb push hello /data/local/tmp/he=
llo<br>adb shell chmod +x /data/local/tmp/hello</span></pre><p id=3D"5441" =
class=3D"pw-post-body-paragraph nq nr ho ns b im nt nu nv ip nw nx ny nz oa=
 ob oc od oe of og oh oi oj ok ol hh bg" data-selectable-paragraph=3D"">And=
